This simple tool, consisting of 25 questions, is used around the world by researchers and clinicians to assess the strengths and difficulties of young people and it is what we use here at Elk City public schools to measure the efficacy of the support programs we are implementing through Project AWARE. This questionnaire is 25 questions long. Students 5th grade and up click a link that takes them to the questionnaire and they answer the questions for themselves. post_text:
A Teachers Work Is Never Done:
Mrs. Gwen Pasby was my second grade teacher. I was not a good student in school and I can assure you there would have been nothing about me that would lead you to believe I would accomplish anything in life, but Mrs. Pasby saw something in me. Over the past 47 years since our meeting in the second grade she has never failed to write me a note of support or congratulations anytime she saw or heard my name. My career has taken me to six different towns and it never failed, out of the blue I would get a note from her. I can assure everyone the past five months have not been easy for educators. It‚Äôs nice to know in a world of cynics there are people like Mrs. Pasby. I received the following this morning and thought I would share.
Rick Garrison, Superintendent
Elk City Public Schools

post_text: Parents, we are using SchoolMessenger for our only communication system from our staff and teachers. We would like to be able to send you text messages through SchoolMessenger. To do so, you must opt in. We can't send you texts without you opting in. To opt in, simply text Yes to 67587. If you've already opted in and are getting texts, you don't need to do this again. If you're not receiving texts from us, opt in first and then contact each of your children's schools and make sure your phone number is current. You'll have to opt in from each cell phone number on which you'd like to receive texts. Thank you.

Are you as confused as we are about Covid-19? Drs. Robinson and Greenway sit down with Superintendent Rick Garrison to talk real talk about the virus, what we can do to slow it down and the plans to return school. Knowledge is power and an effective tool to combat anxiety. Big thanks to Dr. Robinson and Dr. Greenway for taking time from their day to visit with us! Elk City is so lucky to have them!

post_text:
We know there are many discussions and rumors circulating about two really hot topics right now: mask and school start date. The Elk City Administration would like to address those two things.

School is scheduled to start in person on August 13. We feel that the calendar as we have it set will allow us to phase into the school year and prepare for what may come. Students are in school two days the first week. That will give us the weekend to make any adjustments that may arise. Then we have two solid weeks of school. This will give staff time to familiarize students with online learning platforms and other procedures that have changed. Then in September, we have several four day weeks. The‚Ä¶ More

Elk City Elementary
April 27 at 12:44 PM ¬∑

Pre-K Enrollment for Fall 2020 is coming May 1st-May 10th, and it's online!
Elk City Public Schools will be offering our new fully-online enrollment this year! Watch our page this Friday, May 1st for the live link to begin your child's enrollment. The link will take you to a registration page where you will fill out your basic information. You will then receive an email with the link to complete your child's pre-k enrollment. There, you can conveniently enroll your child from your home or anywhere using your phone, tablet or computer. You will even be able to upload copies of your child's shot record, birth certificate and proof of residency. No more waiting in line or bringing copies to the school!

Your child must be 4 years old on or before September 1, 2020 in order to be eligible.

The first 150 to enroll will be guaranteed a spot, so we encourage you to enroll this Friday.

Please share to help us spread the word!

We've thrown a significant amount of information at you lately about our district closure and what education at Elk City Public Schools will look like starting Monday, April 6. So, for more than you've ever wanted to know about this closure, click the attached link or go to our website (www.elkcityschools.com) and click Covid-19 Info in the top right corner. This page has a link for each school's most current plan and procedures for dealing with this ongoing, changing situation. The top of each school's page also has a Covid-19 Info link.

Thank you all for your support and cooperation.

Dear parents please share this:
Elk City 7th and 8th grade band students may come to the band room to get instruments Thursday and Friday between the hours of 5:00 pm & 7:00 pm April 2nd and 3rd. We will have a table outside the band room in the east parking lot of the Susan Powell building. We will be following CDC guidelines and ask that everyone observe the 6‚Äô social distancing protocol and once items have been collected we ask that you go home and not socialize. Students will be allowed to enter, one at a time, to get their instruments and music. Some students still have fundraiser money out and we ask that you turn in the money at that time. We will have packets with assignments, a pacing guide and instructions available at that time. Thank you for supporting your child in our program during this challenging time.

post_text:
Elk City Public Schools to begin ‚ÄúMobile Meal‚Äù distribution on Monday, March 23, 2020.

These ‚Äúgrab and go‚Äù meals will be offered at no cost to children 18-years old or younger and to those with disabilities that are 21-years-old or younger. Children must be present to receive the meals. They don‚Äôt have to get out of the car, but must be able to be seen.

Elk City Public Schools has designated 10 stops in our community where these meals will be distributed Monday-Friday. Those participating will receive a nutritious lunch as well as breakfast for the next day.

We will follow the recommendations of social distancing and request that students do not eat at the drop off locations, but take them home.

See FAQ released on Friday for drop off map and times.

Elk City Public Schools has designated 10 stops in our community where these meals will be distributed Monday-Friday. Those participating will receive a nutritious lunch as well as breakfast for the next day.

We will follow the recommendations of social distancing and request that students do not eat at the drop off locations, but take them home.

See FAQ released on Friday for drop off map and times.

Parents and Guardians of Elk City Public School Students,
You may have heard that Elk City Public Schools was awarded the Project AWARE (Advancing Wellness and Resiliency in Education)Grant. The focus of the five-year grant is addressing the social, emotional, and mental health needs of our students.
As one of the grant activities, your student or their teacher will be asked to complete the SDQ (Strengths and Difficulties Questionnaire) on March 25th, 2020. This is a brief screening questionnaire for PK-12th grade students. If you choose for your student to not participate in the screening process, feel free to stop by the Board of Education at 300 N Boone Street to complete a declination form. The deadline for completing a declination form is March 24th, 2020.
We are excited about how Project AWARE has and will continue to help our students.

post_text: Elk City FFA members Kai Oster, Natalee Pryor, Campbell Jacobsma, and Braxton Buchanan along with advisor Karie Dillinger (names are in order of photo with Lt. Gov) met with other FFA members across the state at the Capitol building on Tues, Feb 18. FFA Day at the Capitol kicks off National FFA Week activities for many chapters. The Elk City delegation got a brief tour from Representative Todd Russ, discussed college and goal setting with Speaker Pro Tempore Harold Wright and got to meet Lieutenant Governor Matt Pinnell. Elk City's FFA members also visited Senator Darcy Jech's office, spoke with State Superintendent of Education Joy Hoffmeister and saw Secretary of Agriculture Blayne Arthur. These 9th grade students had never been to our state's capitol building so it was a truly educational day!

Elk City Project AWARE and the Community Coalition Team invite you to apply the science of hope in your daily life to overcome the trauma, adversity, and struggles everyone must face. Hope is the most predictive indicator of well-being in a person‚Äôs life. Hope is measurable. Hope is malleable. Hope changes lives. On February 25th, Dr. Chan Hellman will provide a roadmap to measure hope in your life, assess what may have robbed you of the power of hope, and then will provide strategies to increase hope. Dr. Hellman's work challenges every person to be transparent and honest about their own stories of struggle and adversity, calls for the end of shame and blame in addressing the struggles of those who have experienced trauma, illness, or abuse, and provides practical ways to increase your Hope score and thrive because of it.
Have you registered for your FREE ticket to this life changing event?
